[02:19.90]CLARENCE	O, no, my dream was lengthen'd after life;
[02:23.09]	O, then began the tempest to my soul,
[02:26.00]	Who pass'd, methought, the melancholy flood,
[02:29.33]	With that grim ferryman which poets write of,
[02:32.86]	Unto the kingdom of perpetual night.
[02:35.77]	The first that there did greet my stranger soul,
[02:39.52]	Was my great father-in-law, renowned Warwick;
[02:42.98]	Who cried aloud, 'What scourge for perjury
[02:46.24]	Can this dark monarchy afford false Clarence?'
[02:49.78]	And so he vanish'd: then came wandering by
[02:53.11]	A shadow like an angel, with bright hair
[02:56.30]	Dabbled in blood; and he squeak'd out aloud,
[02:59.69]	'Clarence is come; false, fleeting, perjured Clarence,
[03:03.58]	That stabb'd me in the field by Tewksbury;
[03:06.90]	Seize on him, Furies, take him to your torments!'
[03:10.51]	With that, methoughts, a legion of foul fiends
[03:14.04]	Environ'd me about, and howled in mine ears
[03:17.44]	Such hideous cries, that with the very noise
[03:20.91]	I trembling waked, and for a season after
[03:24.17]	Could not believe but that I was in hell,
[03:27.42]	Such terrible impression made the dream.
[03:30.61]BRAKENBURY	No marvel, my lord, though it affrighted you;
[03:34.01]	I promise, I am afraid to hear you tell it.
[03:37.34]CLARENCE	O Brakenbury, I have done those things,
[03:40.39]	Which now bear evidence against my soul,
[03:43.58]	For Edward's sake; and see how he requites me!
[03:47.11]	O God! if my deep prayers cannot appease thee,
[03:50.65]	But thou wilt be avenged on my misdeeds,
[03:53.84]	Yet execute thy wrath in me alone,
[03:56.61]	O, spare my guiltless wife and my poor children!
[04:00.29]	I pray thee, gentle keeper, stay by me;
[04:03.27]	My soul is heavy, and I fain would sleep.
[04:06.46]BRAKENBURY	I will, my lord: God give your grace good rest!
[04:09.99]	[CLARENCE sleeps]
[04:10.82]	Sorrow breaks seasons and reposing hours,
[04:14.08]	Makes the night morning, and the noon-tide night.
[04:17.83]	Princes have but their tides for their glories,
[04:21.50]	An outward honour for an inward toil;
[04:24.48]	And, for unfelt imagination,
[04:26.77]	They often feel a world of restless cares:
[04:30.10]	So that, betwixt their tides and low names,
[04:33.42]	There's nothing differs but the outward fame.
[04:36.96]	[Enter the two Murderers]
[04:37.79]First Murderer	Ho! who's here?
[04:39.18]BRAKENBURY	In God's name what are you, and how came you hither?
[04:43.13]First Murderer	I would speak with Clarence, and I came hither on my legs.
[04:47.50]BRAKENBURY	Yea, are you so brief?
[04:49.37]Second Murderer	O sir, it is better to be brief than tedious. Show
[04:53.18]	him our commission; talk no more.
[04:55.82]	[BRAKENBURY reads it]
[04:56.65]BRAKENBURY	I am, in this, commanded to deliver
[04:59.42]	The noble Duke of Clarence to your hands:
[05:02.68]	I will not reason what is meant hereby,
[05:05.80]	Because I will be guiltless of the meaning.
[05:09.20]	Here are the keys, there sits the duke asleep:
[05:12.73]	I'll to the king; and signify to him
[05:15.64]	That thus I have resign'd my charge to you.
[05:19.04]First Murderer	Do so, it is a point of wisdom: fare you well.
[05:22.51]	[Exit BRAKENBURY]
[05:23.34]Second Murderer	What, shall we stab him as he sleeps?
[05:26.25]First Murderer	No; then he will say 'twas done cowardly, when he wakes.
[05:30.34]Second Murderer	When he wakes! why, fool, he shall never wake till
[05:34.09]	the judgment-day.
[05:35.68]First Murderer	Why, then he will say we stabbed him sleeping.
[05:39.22]Second Murderer	The urging of that word 'judgment' hath bred a kind
[05:43.10]	of remorse in me.
[05:44.69]First Murderer	What, art thou afraid?
[05:46.57]Second Murderer	Not to kill him, having a warrant for it; but to be
[05:50.45]	damned for killing him, from which no warrant can defend us.
[05:54.95]First Murderer	I thought thou hadst been resolute.
[05:57.80]Second Murderer	So I am, to let him live.
[05:59.88]First Murderer	Back to the Duke of Gloucester, tell him so.
[06:03.27]Second Murderer	I pray thee, stay a while: I hope my holy humour
[06:06.95]	will change; 'twas wont to hold me but while one
[06:10.62]	would tell twenty.
[06:12.29]First Murderer	How dost thou feel thyself now?
[06:14.85]Second Murderer	'Faith, some certain dregs of conscience are yet
[06:18.53]	within me.
[06:19.63]First Murderer	Remember our reward, when the deed is done.
[06:22.96]Second Murderer	'Zounds, he dies: I had forgot the reward.
[06:26.08]First Murderer	Where is thy conscience now?
[06:28.44]Second Murderer	In the Duke of Gloucester's purse.
[06:31.21]First Murderer	So when he opens his purse to give us our reward,
[06:35.03]	thy conscience flies out.
[06:37.17]Second Murderer	Let it go; there's few or none will entertain it.
[06:40.92]First Murderer	How if it come to thee again?
[06:43.34]Second Murderer	I'll not meddle with it: it is a dangerous thing: it
[06:47.30]	makes a man a coward: a man cannot steal, but it
[06:50.97]	accuseth him; he cannot swear, but it cheques him;
[06:54.71]	he cannot lie with his neighbour's wife, but it
[06:58.39]	detects him: 'tis a blushing shamefast spirit that
[07:02.20]	mutinies in a man's bosom; it fills one full of
[07:05.88]	obstacles: it made me once restore a purse of gold
[07:09.76]	that I found; it beggars any man that keeps it: it
[07:13.57]	is turned out of all towns and cities for a
[07:17.04]	dangerous thing; and every man that means to live
[07:20.85]	well endeavours to trust to himself and to live
[07:24.59]	without it.
[07:25.77]First Murderer	'Zounds, it is even now at my elbow, persuading me
[07:29.52]	not to kill the duke.
[07:31.39]Second Murderer	Take the devil in thy mind, and relieve him not: he
